        "content": "This is logic’s workhorse: If A then B. A is true. Therefore B is true. Example: 'If it rains, the ground gets wet. It’s raining. Therefore, the ground is wet.' The mind loves this simplicity because it mirrors how reality behaves—causes bring effects. Modus ponens feels almost like breathing once you recognize it."
      },
      {
        "id": "2.1.19",
        "title": "Modus Tollens—Denying the End",
        "content": "Another solid pattern: If A then B. B is false. Therefore A is false. Example: 'If it’s raining, the ground is wet. The ground isn’t wet, so it isn’t raining.' Deduction flexes both ways—affirming beginnings and denying endings. Learn these patterns, and you’ll start spotting them woven through debates, ads, and even your own inner dialogue."
      },
      {
        "id": "2.1.20",
        "title": "When Form Fails",
        "content": "Break the pattern and certainty dies. 'If A then B. B is true, so A must be true.'—that’s the fallacy of affirming the consequent. 'If A then B. Not A, so not B.'—denying the antecedent. Both sound logical but secretly short-circuit. Deduction demands respect for sequence; skip one link, and the chain of necessity snaps."
      },
     
