      "content": "Syllogisms are logic’s purest expression of form. Each one holds a major premise, a minor premise, and a conclusion that clicks neatly into place. 'All trees need sunlight. This oak is a tree. Therefore, this oak needs sunlight.' Notice the precision—each statement aligns like gears. Once the first two are accepted, the third follows automatically. It’s not persuasion; it’s mechanical truth, a gear-train turning in the mind until the outcome locks in place."
    },
    {
      "id": "2.1.22",
