      "content": "To admit your reasoning was flawed is an act of strength. Revision is repair, not retreat. Every time you refine an argument, you model intellectual honesty—the courage to value truth over ego. Sound thinkers aren’t always right; they’re just always improving."
    },
    {
      "id": "2.4.47",
      "title": "The Ethics of Reasoning",
      "content": "Reasoning has moral weight. The moment your words influence others, your logic becomes an ethical act. Soundness ensures that what persuades also uplifts—that we use clarity as a tool for understanding, not manipulation. Thinking clearly is a responsibility, not just a skill."
    },
    {
      "id": "2.4.48",
      "title": "Soundness as Respect",
      "content": "Sound reasoning is respect in intellectual form. It respects truth enough to test it, others enough to hear them, and yourself enough to stay curious. The way you argue reflects how you regard the world: as something to control or something to understand."
    },
